`Effect.orElse` is the right tool when the recovery path is *another effect of the same success type* — no handler argument, no tag inspection, just "if this fails, try that." Writing the same thing with `Effect.catchAll((_e) => other)` works but hides the intent: the reader has to notice you discard `_e`. `orElse` also composes naturally with chains, so `a.orElse(b).orElse(c)` reads as "first success wins".

